It is no secret that crypto currently represents the frontier of technological innovation.

In the last cycle, the game was simpler. Most of the activity happened on $ETH and Ethereum DeFi coins. Today we have more altcoins than ever before, and with more quality ecosystems than I can count with both of my hands. 

Many OGs will describe this cycle as the hardest so far. I only entered crypto in 2021, but I think this one is definitely harder too. From chasing airdrops the normal way to instead focusing on points farming with more or less already knowing the outcome and the size of the airdrop.

So far this cycle the biggest change is the dispersion in the space. We are conditioned to think that altcoins will pump together. But now there are probably 300 decent projects. There is not enough liquidity for all of them to pump.

Remember there are a lot more tokens with â€œutilityâ€ on the market today than in 2021. Every week now 3-5 â€œqualityâ€ coins are added to the market. Total3 mcap goes up, and everyone seems happy. But ask yourself who is going to buy all these tokens. Unless institutions or retail are coming in masses, it will just be a forever PvP fight.

New shiny coins are good (until the circulating supply increases).

Since investors are locked up for a long time on low float tokens, this means that when they finally start unlocking it will be a constant sell pressure on the market.

Okay, so more and more supply will hit the market as tokens unlock gradually.

But the question is: where is the demand? Who will buy the tokens that is getting dumped on you?

You could argue that because of narrative X, Y, and Z, the price will go up, increased TVL in a DeFi protocol, a bullish event, etc., and this can work for a while. But at some point, the supply will outnumber the demand and we will start spiraling downwards due to massive inflation.

Early buyers will get trapped, which leads to bearish sentiment among the community, reduced TVL in the protocol/protocols, devs (if any) leaving for greener fields, team members quitting, etc.

The new question for 2024 is this: If the yield/money is captured in the point farming phase, then why trade the token after it is launched at all?

Still curious about what will happen to eg. Ethena when their airdrop season 2 will finish. People are locking up USDe for points atm, but will they still hold it when there is no points left to farm? The staked version of USDe makes sense though because of the real yield (funding rate + ETH staking rewards). Not going to ponder more about this now, but letâ€™s see what happens.

Given the plethora of information present in 2024, identifying signals from noise is the single most important skillset in driving returns. Our goal as investors is to maximize return over the long term. This does not mean that we need to maximize returns every waking moment.

With that said, I am not sure what's the best way to capture the most upside going forward. Being it memecoins, max longing $ETH , a few selected altcoin longs, pair trading with a basket of high FDV, low float tokens combined with the latest narrative longs, DeFi yield farming. In retrospect for the first 6 months of 2024 it looks like points farming, being a part of private phases of protocols and DeFi yield farming has been the best bets + ETH ETF trade/Van Eck SOL ETF and a few other news trading events.

I continue to be long on the industry I am logging into every single day to talk about with my degenerative friends. The tide will turn, eventually.

#EthereumLayer 2@Optimism/@baserisks continued. 

Do not underestimate these risks. Remember this post.

Note:@coinbaseBase blockchain is a fork of the@Optimismcodebase.

1) Optimism architecture backs the entire Layer 2 with reserves of $ETH in single Ethereum wallets. This is a permissioned relationship and humans with keys can access these wallets. This is not web3. This is not permissionless. Neither Base or Optimism is web3 until this is permissionless.

2) The Optimism blockchain relies on a single sequencer to process transactions, which introduces some centralization risks. If the sequencer becomes compromised or acts maliciously, it could impact the integrity of the blockchain. While Optimism is designed to be decentralized, the current implementation relies on a single sequencer, which could potentially become a single point of failure.

I will continue to raise awareness. This is the biggest risk in crypto.
